{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:49:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:49:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16113"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16113"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.89,0.02,0.05,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63947"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8804"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49377"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"140"},{"type":"tags","id":"2868"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"10738"},{"type":"tags","id":"10741"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63947"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EKlinefelter syndrome is one of the most common sex chromosome disorders, affecting approximately 1 in 500-1,000 male births.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic feature of Klinefelter syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["47,XXY karyotype","Increased testosterone production","Short stature","Early onset of puberty","Normal fertility"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hallmark of Klinefelter syndrome is a \u003Cstrong\u003E47,XXY karyotype\u003C/strong\u003E, resulting from non-disjunction during meiosis. This leads to hypogonadism and testosterone deficiency, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased testosterone production\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMales with Klinefelter syndrome typically have tall rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort stature\u003C/strong\u003E, due to the presence of additional X chromosome genes affecting growth. They do not have \u003Cstrong\u003Eearly onset of puberty\u003C/strong\u003E; instead, puberty is often delayed or incomplete.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese individuals typically have \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal fertility\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as most men with Klinefelter syndrome are infertile due to azoospermia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther characteristic features include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGynaecomastia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESmall, firm testes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EReduced facial and body hair\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELearning difficulties\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDelayed motor development\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Klinefelter syndrome is characterized by a 47,XXY karyotype resulting from non-disjunction during meiosis.","Males with Klinefelter syndrome typically present with tall stature, hypogonadism, and reduced testosterone levels.","Features of Klinefelter syndrome include gynaecomastia, small testes, and infertility due to azoospermia."],"references":["Groth KA, Skakkeb\u00e6k A, H\u00f8st C, Gravholt CH, Bojesen A. Clinical review: Klinefelter syndrome--a clinical update. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2013 Jan;98(1):20-30. doi: 10.1210/jc.2012-2382. Epub 2012 Nov 1. PMID: 23118429.","Bonomi M, Rochira V, Pasquali D, Balercia G, Jannini EA, Ferlin A; Klinefelter ItaliaN Group (KING). Klinefelter syndrome (KS): genetics, clinical phenotype and hypogonadism. J Endocrinol Invest. 2017 Feb;40(2):123-134. doi: 10.1007/s40618-016-0541-6. Epub 2016 Sep 19. PMID: 27644703; PMCID: PMC5269463.","Butler G, Srirangalingam U, Faithfull J, Sangster P, Senniappan S, Mitchell R. Klinefelter syndrome: going beyond the diagnosis. Arch Dis Child. 2023 Mar;108(3):166-171. doi: 10.1136/archdischild-2020-320831. Epub 2022 Aug 10. PMID: 35948402; PMCID: PMC7614197.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49377"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16113"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49377"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T19:52:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T18:26:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8804"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63947"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"